{{primary|date=November 2016}} The '''first Catilinarian conspiracy''' was a plot to murder the [[Roman consul|consuls]] of 65 BC and seize power. Historians consider it unlikely that [[Catiline]] would have been involved in the first Catilinarian conspiracy or, indeed, that the conspiracy existed at all.{{cn|date=November 2016}}
==History== [[File:Comic History of Rome Table 10 Cicero denouncing Catiline.jpg|thumb|300px|Comic depiction of Cicero denouncing Catiline. (Note [[anachronism]]s, such as [[top hat]]s and other [[Victorian fashion|Victorian clothing]].)]] In all likelihood, [[Catiline]] was not involved in the so-called first Catilinarian conspiracy, although several historical sources implicate him in it. There does not seem to be a single account that is represented in all of the sources: rather, it seems that the accounts represent a collection of rumors accusing different political figures in attempts to tarnish their names. As it pertains to Catiline, much of the information originates in [[Cicero]]’s speech ''[[In Toga Candida]]'' which was given during his election campaign in 64 BC. Only fragments of this speech still exist, in the later writing of [[Asconius Pedianus]].{{cn|date=November 2016}}
The [[Roman consul|consuls-designate]], [[Publius Autronius Paetus]] and [[Publius Cornelius Sulla]], were prevented from entering office because of ''[[ambitus]]'', electoral corruption, under the ''[[Lex Acilia Calpurnia]]''.<ref name="cic_sulla_49">Cicero, ''Pro Sulla'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text.jsp?doc=Cic.+Sul.+49&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0015 XLIX]; Sallust, ''Bellum Catilinae'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text.jsp?doc=Sal.+Cat.+18.2&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0123 XVIII.2]</ref> Thus, the two other leading candidates, [[Lucius Manlius Torquatus]] and [[Lucius Aurelius Cotta (consul 65 BC)|Lucius Aurelius Cotta]], were elected in a second election and were to enter office on January 1, 65 BC. Supposedly, Catiline, incensed because he was not allowed to stand for the consulship, conspired with [[Gnaeus Calpurnius Piso (Catilinian conspirator)|Gnaeus Calpurnius Piso]] and the former consuls-designate to slaughter many of the senators and the new consuls the day they assumed office. Then they would name themselves the consuls for the year and then Piso would have been sent to organize the provinces in [[Hispania]].<ref name="sall_18.5">Sallust, ''Bellum Catilinae'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text.jsp?doc=Perseus:text:1999.02.0123:section=18 XVIII.5]; Asconius 92C; Dio Cassius [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/36*.html#44.3 XXXVI.44.3]</ref> Alternatively, [[Suetonius]] claims that [[Julius Caesar]] and [[Marcus Licinius Crassus]] directed the conspiracy, but he fails to mention Catiline's involvement. Instead of assuming the consulship, Crassus is accused of planning to become [[Roman Dictator|dictator]] and intending to name Caesar ''[[magister equitum]]''.<ref name="sue_9">Suetonius, ''Divus Julius'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text.jsp?doc=Suet.+Jul.+9&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0061 IX]</ref>
In 62 BC, after Catiline's death, Cicero defended Publius Sulla in court after he was indicted for being a member of the second conspiracy. In order to free his client of implication in the first Catilinarian conspiracy, he places the blame solely on Catiline who, conveniently, had waged war against the [[Roman Republic|Republic]] in the previous months.<ref name="cic_sulla_68">Cicero, ''Pro Sulla'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text.jsp?doc=Perseus:text:1999.02.0015:text=Sul.:section=68 LXVIII]</ref> In the end, Publius Sulla was acquitted, Catiline's name was further tarnished, and Cicero received a large loan to purchase a home.<ref name="gellius_12.12.2-4">Aulus Gellius, ''Noctes Atticae'' XII.12.2-4</ref> It is not clear who participated in this alleged conspiracy, as the different accounts accuse different people, but Catiline's association with it appears to have been developed after the [[Second Catilinarian Conspiracy]]. Cicero's accusations prior to 63 BC are likely unfounded, since Rome had no penalty for libel. Furthermore, Catiline had little motive to participate in this conspiracy, especially since he had been denied very little. He still held the aspiration of obtaining the consulship legitimately the next year, and the conspiracy involved the murder of the consul, Manlius Torquatus, who supported Catiline.
