{{Infobox political party | name = Smokers' Rights Party | logo = | colorcode = <!-- HTML color code (e.g. "red", "#FF0000" or Party metadata color template) otherwise "transparent" --> | leader = | president = | chairman = | general_secretary = | first_secretary = | secretary_general = | presidium = | secretary = | spokesperson = Clinton Mead<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2ser.com/on-air/budget-2016/item/4503-what-is-the-australian-smokers-rights-party |publisher=[[2SER]] |title= What is the Australian Smokers Rights Party? }}</ref> | foundation = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | ideology = [[Single-issue politics]] |position= | headquarters = | international = | website = {{url|http://smokersrights.org.au/}} | country = Australia }} The '''Smokers' Rights Party''' was a registered [[political party]] in [[Australia]] from 2013 until September 2017.<ref name="deregistered">{{cite web |url=http://www.aec.gov.au/Parties_and_Representatives/Party_Registration/Deregistered_parties/files/2017-6278.pdf |title=Notice of deregistration Smokers Rights Party |publisher=[[Australian Electoral Commission]] |date=5 September 2017 |accessdate=13 September 2017 |quote=Notice under s 137(4) of the Commonwealth Electoral Act 1918 On 5 September 2017, Stuart Oreo, acting Assistant Commissioner, as a delegate of the Electoral Commission, deregistered the Smokers Rights Party under subsection 137(4) of the Commonwealth Electoral Act 1918. Reason: s 137(4) – failure to respond to notice under s 137 (1)}}</ref>
The party was created in order to feed preferences to [[David Leyonhjelm]] of the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Australia)|Liberal Democratic Party]].<ref>[http://indaily.com.au/news/2013/12/03/accusations-fly-in-micro-party-stoush/ "Accusations fly in micro-party stoush"], InDaily, 3 December 2013.</ref><ref>[https://www.crikey.com.au/2013/08/22/revealed-the-libertarian-rights-micro-party-links/ "Revealed: the libertarian Right's micro-party links"], Crikey, 22 August 2013.</ref> With the [[Turnbull_Government#Senate_reforms|abolition of group voting tickets]] in 2016, the Smokers' Rights Party was no longer able to act as a preference feeder, and published a statement recommending that supporters vote for Leyonhjelm in the Senate.<ref>[http://smokersrights.org.au "How to vote to protect your rights in the 2016 election"], Smokers' Rights Party.</ref> It was formally deregistered in September 2017.<ref name="deregistered"/>
The Smokers' Rights Party states that it does not receive funding from the tobacco industry.<ref>[http://smokersrights.org.au/links "Links"], Smokers' Rights Party.</ref> Despite this, the Liberal Democrats do, having received at least $35000 from [[Philip Morris International|Philip Morris]] in the 2013-2014 financial year.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2014/oct/02/thank-you-for-smoking-leyonhjelm-confirms-philip-morris-backing "'Thank you for smoking': Leyonhjelm confirms Philip Morris backing"], The Guardian, 2 October 2014.</ref>
Smokers Rights fielded only one candidate in the [[Australian federal election, 2016|2016 federal election]]. This was Joaquim De Lima as a candidate for the [[Division of Fowler]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].<ref name="2016candidates">{{cite web |url=http://www.aec.gov.au/election/candidates.htm |title=Candidates for the 2016 federal election |date=11 June 2016 |access-date=11 June 2016 |publisher=[[Australian Electoral Commission]]}}</ref> De Lima had previously run as a candidate for the [[Outdoor Recreation Party]] ([[Candidates of the New South Wales state election, 2011|NSW 2011 for Penrith]], [[Results for the Australian federal election, 2013 (Senate)#New South Wales|2013 Senate NSW]], [[Australian Senate special election in Western Australia, 2014|2014 senate WA]], [[Candidates of the New South Wales state election, 2015#Legislative Council|2015 NSW upper house]]),<ref>[https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/wa/a/22111577/senate-candidates-dont-live-here/ "Senate candidates don't live here"], The West Australian, 22 March 2014.</ref> and the Liberal Democrats ([[Results of the Australian federal election, 2010 (New South Wales)#Greenway|Federal 2010 for Greenway]]).
